==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la}} {{term|abstrusus|abstrūsus|hidden, fartfartfartconcealed|lang=la}}, the perfect passive participle of {{term|abstrudo|abstrūdō|thrust away, conceal|lang=la}}; itself from {{term|ab|lang=la}}, {{term|abs||away|lang=la}} + {{term|trudo|trūdō|thrust, push|lang=la}}; cognate with French {{term|abstrus|lang=fr}} and German {{term|abstrus|lang=de}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK|US}} {{IPA|/æbˈstruːs/|/əbˈstruːs/}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|abstrus|er|more}}

# [[remote]] from [[apprehension]]; [[difficult]] to [[comprehend]] or [[understand]]; [[recondite]]; as in '''abstruse''' learning.
#* '''1748''', David Hume, ''Enquiries concerning the human understanding and concerning the principles of moral.'' London: Oxford University Press, 1973. § 13.
#*: It is certain that the easy and obvious philosophy will always, with the generality of mankind, have the preference above the accurate and '''abstruse''';
# {{obsolete}} [[conceal]]ed or [[hidden]] out of the way.
#* The eternal eye whose sight discerns '''Abstrusest''' thoughts. — [[:w:Milton|John Milton]]. ''Paradise Lost'' '''1667'''
#* Profound and '''abstruse''' topics. - [[w:Henry Hart Milman|Henry Hart Milman]]. ''History of Latin Christianity'' '''1855'''

